Experiment 1: Setting Up Selenium and Running a Basic “Hello Gmail” Test

Install Java JDK 1.8+
a. Download from Adoptium or Oracle.
b. Run java -version in a terminal or Command Prompt to confirm.

Install Eclipse IDE
a. Download the “Eclipse IDE for Java Developers” package.
b. Unzip and launch eclipse.exe.

Download Selenium Java Client
a. Go to http://seleniumhq.org/download → “Selenium Client & WebDriver Language Bindings (Java)” ZIP.
b. Unzip it into C:\selenium-java\.

Download ChromeDriver
a. Go to https://chromedriver.chromium.org/downloads.
b. Choose the version matching your Chrome browser.
c. Unzip chromedriver.exe into C:\selenium-java\drivers\.

Create Eclipse Project
a. In Eclipse: File → New → Java Project → name: Expt1_Selenium.
b. Right-click the project → New → Folder → enter libs. Repeat for drivers.
c. Copy all .jar files from C:\selenium-java\ into Expt1_Selenium/libs.
d. Copy chromedriver.exe into Expt1_Selenium/drivers.
e. Right-click project → Build Path → Configure Build Path → Libraries → Add JARs… → select every JAR under libs.

Write the Test Code
a. Under src, New → Package → expt1.
b. Under expt1, New → Class → GmailTest (with public static void main).
c. Paste exactly:

java
Copy
Edit
package expt1;

import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;

public class GmailTest {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    // 1. Point to the driver
    System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver",
        "drivers/chromedriver.exe");
    // 2. Launch Chrome
    WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
    // 3. Open Gmail
    driver.get("https://www.gmail.com/");
    // 4. Print & verify title
    String title = driver.getTitle();
    System.out.println("Page title is: " + title);
    if (title.toLowerCase().contains("gmail")) {
      System.out.println("✅ Gmail loaded");
    } else {
      System.out.println("❌ Gmail failed");
    }
    // 5. Close
    driver.quit();
  }
}
Run & Show

Right-click GmailTest.java → Run As → Java Application.

Chrome opens to Gmail; Eclipse console shows:

csharp
Copy
Edit
Page title is: Gmail
✅ Gmail loaded
